content:
Before you set up Unified Knowledge, consider details about third-party knowledge connectors, import and synchronization, generative AI and Einstein for Service, record access and visibility, and search.

Available in: Lightning Experience
Available in: Unlimited Edition and other editions with the Knowledge add-on license
Sources and Connectors:

Adobe Experience Platform (Microsoft Word not supported)
Amazon S3
Atlassian Confluence Cloud
Atlassian Confluence Server
Atlassian Jira Cloud
Custom Source
Google Drive
Guru
MadCap IXIA CCMS (IXIASOFT)
Microsoft Azure (Microsoft Word not supported)
Microsoft SharePoint Online
Microsoft SharePoint Server
Salesforce orgs (for Knowledge)
Sitemap (for external websites)
YouTube
Zendesk

To import and sync a third-party knowledge source, you need the source's credentials. Salesforce syncs knowledge content from third-party sources into the Knowledge Article object every 1 to 2 hours.

Salesforce generative AI makes no distinction between external knowledge and Salesforce Knowledge articles. To ensure that knowledge from a certain source isn't used for grounding AI, use sharing rules to restrict access.

Access to third-party knowledge articles in Salesforce is based on user profiles, data categories, and sharing rules. You can define sharing rules for third-party knowledge the same way you define them for Salesforce Knowledge articles.

Unified Knowledge stores copies of third-party sources to help with cross-source relevance ranking in search results. You can filter by Publish Status, Publication Date, Data Category, and Source field in search results.

Multilingual support is available for Salesforce end-user languages. If you added a third-party knowledge source before July 1, 2024, you must delete it and add it again to use multilingual support.

Only articles in selected languages sync from third-party sources; all others are excluded.
title: Configuring Unified Knowledge in Service Cloud
